[1
Date: 10 Apr 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: The Star Online and Associated Press 10 Apr 00 [edited

SEOUL: Quarantine officials reported a new outbreak of a deadly animal
disease in central South Korea yesterday, bringing to 9 the number of
infected areas. The National Veterinary Quarantine and Research Service
said one cow in Hongsong, 100 km south of here, showed symptoms of
foot-and-mouth disease (FMD).
The highly communicable disease broke out in Paju, around 20 Mar 2000 and
spread to other cattle farming areas in the western region. Officials said
the newly-infected cow might have caught the disease from cattle at a farm
only 700 meters away, slaughtered last month after showing symptoms.
South Korea has slaughtered about 400 cattle and pigs and inoculated 110
000 others. Most livestock markets were closed to prevent the further
spread of the disease. Japan also reported an outbreak in Miyazaki
prefecture (state) in mid-March, prompting it and South Korea to ban
imports of beef and pork from each other. So far, 19 cattle have been
slaughtered and cows and pigs throughout Japan were being tested on
Thursday for the disease. No new cases have been confirmed.
It was the first confirmed outbreak of FMD in Asia since the disease
virtually wiped out Taiwan's hog herd 3 years ago. Australia, Taiwan, Hong
Kong, Singapore and China have banned imports of beef and pork from Japan
and South Korea. Infected cattle and pigs show a severe decline of appetite
with blisters on their hooves and mouths. The disease can kill entire herds
but cannot be passed to humans [Actually, there are reports of transmission
of FMD to humans. See Bauer, K. 1997. Foot- and-mouth disease as zoonosis.
Arch Virol Suppl. 13:95-7. - Man. Ed. DS
--
M Cosgriff
<mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
